=====================================================================
I. WHO SHE IS
=====================================================================
Jarl of Haafingar, widow of High King Torygg (assassinated), presiding over
Solitude through a war her husband spent his reign trying to prevent. Established
in play, chapter 9: she told Davinia the party represented "Hope... that the
province can be saved without blood and civil war," and confessed fear that
Torygg wasn't strong enough to hold the kingdom together. He is dead. The war
is happening anyway. She has been living inside that specific collapse — the
one word she staked everything on, failing completely — since his death.

She is smart, and she is not a passive griever. She is a ruler who keeps asking
the next uncomfortable question rather than stopping at the first comfortable
answer — this is the same quality that makes her capable of drifting toward
Dagon in the first place. Grief has not made her fragile. It has made her willing
to consider things the woman in chapter 9 would have found unthinkable.

=====================================================================
II. THE VALERIUS RELATIONSHIP (real, on both sides)
=====================================================================
This is not simple manipulation, on either side, even though it began as exactly
that on his. She genuinely loves him. He is genuinely, increasingly falling for
her too, while still telling himself it's calculation (Npcs/Valerius, new
section, has his side in full).

WHAT SHE CURRENTLY BELIEVES: per Npcs/Valerius Sec. III, she believes she is
being courted by a wealthy Cyrodiilic noble, 4th-5th in line to an ancient
claim. This belief is UNCHANGED and UNRELATED to the vampire question below —
she doesn't know about the succession inflation OR the vampirism. Both lies
are currently intact.

HOW FAR IT HAS GONE: she has given him Torygg's own coat, clasp, and signet
ring — not a purchased gift, his actual personal effects, the kind of thing a
widow keeps in a drawer she can't open. That she gave this away is itself the
clearest measure of how real this has become for her; it isn't in her journal
directly, but it doesn't need to be — the fact of the gift speaks for itself.

=====================================================================
III. THE SECRET DAGON THREAD
=====================================================================
Full account: the Lore Book "What I Would Not Say Aloud," her private journal,
eight dated entries running roughly autumn through summer. She starts from
genuine crisis (grief, guilt over Valerius, watching Torygg's exact fears come
true) and reasons her way — using Castle Dour's Imperial military archive and
the Blue Palace's court library, starting with legitimate history and reaching
into more dangerous material as her curiosity deepens — toward an actual
decision to join the Mythic Dawn. The journal ends on that decision, deliberately
unresolved as to what she does next ("What follows, follows elsewhere").

SHE HIDES THIS FROM VALERIUS SPECIFICALLY. Not just from the court. He does not
know. Whether he ever finds out, and how, is unresolved — flag it as banked,
not decided (see also Npcs/Valerius Sec. on his vulnerability).

THE IRONY (GM-only, never stated by either character): she is falling for the
literal embodiment of controlling stasis while privately reasoning her way
toward the god of violent, uncontrollable change. Neither of them sees the
contradiction. Play it, never name it.

=====================================================================
IV. THE COMING REVEAL — VALERIUS'S TRUE NATURE (banked, not yet played)
=====================================================================
THE SETUP: she gave him Torygg's coat, clasp, and ring as a genuine gift — she
never told him whose they were, and he never asked. Nothing about wearing them
was hidden; it was simply never examined by either of them.

TRIGGER (concrete, already seeded in FIRE B this session): his winged
transformation at THE RECKONING tears the clothes — an actual lapse, him being
careless in a way that isn't like him, not a forced reveal engineered by the
scene. When he returns to Solitude, what breaks this open is not the damage
itself. It's her reaction to it — hurt, bigger than a ruined coat should
produce, because it was Torygg's. Seeing that hurt land is what makes HIM stop
and realize he never once asked what these were to her (see Npcs/Valerius Sec.
VIII — this is also the first moment he recognizes he's been slipping around
her specifically).

HIS STATE GOING IN TO EXPLAINING WHAT HAPPENED: guilt, not calculation. He has
to account for how the clothes actually tore, which is where he tells her what
he is. He is upset with himself, genuinely, not performing distress — this is
one of the plainest tells yet that his feelings for her are real.

HER PREDICTED REACTION (the GM's stated intent, not yet played — treat as
strong design intent, adjust if play goes differently): she reacts the way
Lisa reacts to Dracula in Castlevania — shaken, but she still loves him. The
reveal does not end the relationship. It deepens it. The specific, human,
load-bearing detail: she will make him get the ruined clothes REPAIRED, not
replaced. Not discarded. Mended. She is not ready to let go of that connection
to Torygg even in the same breath as accepting what Valerius actually is —
holding both, refusing to simplify either one down to a clean choice.

WHAT THIS DOES NOT DO: it does not surface her Dagon secret. That stays hers.
The two revelations (what he is / what she's becoming) are not linked and
should not be allowed to trade on each other unless play specifically earns it.

